Gapminder

For this assignment, we are going to use the dataset gapminder. Gapminder includes information about economics, population, and life expectancy from countries all over the world. You will need to install it before use. This is the same data that we used for the practice midterm. You may want to load that assignment for reference.

#install.packages("gapminder")
library("gapminder")

Questions

The questions below are open-ended and have many possible solutions. Your approach should, where appropriate, include numerical summaries and visuals. Be creative; assume you are building an analysis that you would ultimately present to an audience of stakeholders. Feel free to try out different geoms if they more clearly present your results.

2. Among the interesting variables in gapminder is life expectancy. How has global life expectancy changed between 1952 and 2007?

gapminder %>% 
  group_by(year) %>% 
  summarize(min=min(lifeExp),
            mean=mean(lifeExp),
            max=max(lifeExp))
## # A tibble: 12 x 4

gapminder %>% 
  group_by(year) %>% 
  summarize(mean=mean(lifeExp)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=year, y=mean))+
  geom_line()

3. How do the distributions of life expectancy compare for the years 1952 and 2007? Challenge: Can you put both distributions on a single plot?

gapminder %>% 
  filter(year==1952 | year==2007) %>% 
  mutate(year=as.factor(year)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=lifeExp, group=year, fill=year))+
  geom_density(alpha=0.5)

5. How has life expectancy changed between 1952-2007 for each continent? Try using geom_line() for this, including all continents on the same plot.

gapminder %>% 
  group_by(year, continent) %>% 
  summarize(mean=mean(lifeExp)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=year, y=mean, group=continent, color=continent))+
  geom_line()

6. We are interested in the relationship between per capita GDP and life expectancy; i.e. does having more money help you live longer?

gapminder %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=gdpPercap, y=lifeExp))+
  geom_point()+
  labs(title = "GDP vs. Life Expectancy",
       x = "GDP per capita",
       y = "Life expectancy")

7. There is extreme disparity in per capita GDP. Rescale the x axis to make this easier to interpret. How would you characterize the relationship?

gapminder %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=gdpPercap, y=lifeExp))+
  geom_point()+
  scale_x_log10()+
  geom_smooth(method=lm, se=F)+
  labs(title = "GDP vs. Life Expectancy",
       x = "GDP per capita (log 10)",
       y = "Life expectancy")

8. Which countries have had the largest population growth since 1952?

gapminder %>% 
  select(country, year, pop) %>% 
  filter(year==1952 | year==2007) %>% 
  pivot_wider(names_from = year,
              names_prefix = "yr_",
              values_from = pop) %>% 
  mutate(delta= yr_2007-yr_1952) %>% 
  arrange(desc(delta))

9. Use your results from the question above to plot population growth for the top five countries since 1952.

gapminder %>% 
  filter(country=="China" | country=="India" | country=="United States" | country=="Indonesia" | country=="Brazil") %>% 
  select(country, year, pop) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=year, y=pop, color=country))+
  geom_line()

10. How does per capita GDP growth compare between these same five countries?

gapminder %>% 
  filter(country=="China" | country=="India" | country=="United States" | country=="Indonesia" | country=="Brazil") %>% 
  select(year, country, gdpPercap) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=year, y=gdpPercap, group=country, color=country))+
  geom_line()
